title: Chinese hackers breach US Treasury; Third-party alert triggers cybersecurity probe
description: Chinese hackers breached the US Treasury by exploiting a third-party software service, accessing unclassified documents and workstations. The investigation, led by the FBI and other agencies, links the attack to state-sponsored activities by China. The Treasury is enhancing its cybersecurity measures and collaborating with partners to safeguard their systems.
author: TOI World Desk

title: Texas governor slammed for offering condolences to Jimmy Carter's late wife
description: Texas Governor Greg Abbott faced criticism after mistakenly including condolences for Rosalynn Carter, who passed in 2023, in his statement for Jimmy Carter's death. Abbott swiftly corrected the error after public backlash. This follows other past blunders, such as sharing a satirical article as real news. Abbott also ordered Texas flags at half-mast for Carter.
author: TOI World Desk

title: Live Aid campaigner Bob Geldof was ‘scathing about African leaders’, files reveal
description: Singer urged Tony Blair not to appoint African co-chair to commission on aid, UK government papers showThe Live Aid campaigner Bob Geldof urged Tony Blair not to appoint an African co-chair to the UK-led organisation working to overhaul international aid to the continent because he thought African leadership was “very weak” on the issue, newly released government documents suggest.The singer was “scathing about the ability and worthiness of virtually all African leaders” before the establishment in 2004 of Blair’s Commission for Africa, which would produce a report, Our Common Interest, and prompt a landmark pledge by rich nations to boost aid and write off debt. Continue reading...
author: Caroline Davies

title: Labour government discussed Tanzania asylum camp plan in 2004, files show
description: Newly released files show proposals to divert £2m – earmarked to prevent conflict in Africa – to fund schemeTony Blair’s government discussed diverting £2m earmarked to prevent conflict in Africa in order to fund a controversial pilot scheme to process and house asylum-seekers in Tanzania, newly released government files show.Under the scheme, Britain would have offered Tanzania an extra £4m in aid if it opened an asylum camp to house people claiming to be Somalian refugees while their applications to live in Britain were assessed.
